# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asian-test-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] The **1912 Triangular Tournament** was a Test cricket competition played between Australia, England and South Africa, the only Test-playing nations at the time.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] The ultimate winners of the tournament were England, with four wins in their six matches, but the tournament was deemed a failure, with disappointing crowds and uncompetitive cricket, caused in part by a weakened Australia team.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] The tournament was the first tournament in Test history to be played between more than two nations.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] It was the only such tournament until the Asian Test Championships of 1998–99 and 2001–02, and the ICC World Test Championship which began in 2019.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] The idea of a competition involving all three of the nations then playing Test cricket (Australia, England and South Africa) was proposed at the first meeting of the Imperial Cricket Conference in July 1909.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] The original proposal was for a tournament to be held every four years, with the first hosted by England in 1912.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] For a variety of reasons, the tournament was not a success.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] The summer was one of the wettest since records began in 1766: rainfall in the three months of June, July and August was more than twice the seasonal average, and August, 1912, was the coolest, dullest and wettest August of the 20th century.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] At that time, pitches were not covered to protect them against rain, so the batsmen were at a distinct disadvantage on the proverbial sticky wicket.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] These problems were exacerbated since Tests in England were in those days played over three days rather than the five days that is now usual.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] In addition, disputes between the players and management in Australia meant that six leading Australian players refused to tour whilst medical duties meant “Ranji” Hordern, easily Australia’s best bowler in the 1911–12 Ashes series, could not tour either.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] These setbacks severely weakened a team that had otherwise been level with England in recent Ashes series.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] The leg spin and googly bowlers in the South African team were very effective on the matting pitches then in use in South Africa, but were less deadly on English grass pitches.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] As a result, England dominated, winning four of their six matches and drawing the other two.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] The tournament was so unsuccessful that it has never been repeated.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] The idea of a tournament of international cricket matches between more than two countries was not repeated, outside of regional tournaments in East Africa and the West Indies, until the invention of One Day International cricket and the first Women's Cricket World Cup in 1973.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] The only other Test cricket tournaments in history were the Asian Test Championships played in 1998–99 and 2001–02, which were also not great successes, until the ICC World Test Championship began in 2019.
[src:asian-test-championship/1912-triangular-tournament] Perhaps the most notable incident of the series was Australian bowler Jimmy Matthews taking two hat-tricks in the same Test match, one in each innings of the opening match against South Africa, the only time a bowler has taken two hat-tricks in the same Test.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] The first Asian Test Championship, organized by the Asian Cricket Council was held between 16 February and 16 March 1999.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] India, Pakistan and Sri Lanka competed in the tournament; Bangladesh could not compete because the ICC had not granted them Test status.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] This tournament was considered to be the predecessor to the Test Cricket World Cup that the ICC was planning for the nine member nations.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] The tournament was almost canceled in January 1999 due to tour conflicts, television rights and security concerns.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] Three round-robin tournament matches were played with each team meeting each other once and the top two sides playing a final.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] A win was worth 12 points, a tie 6 points and no points were awarded for a draw or loss.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] In addition to this, bonus points were awarded to teams for bowling and batting performances (see Scoring system).
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] The venues of the round robin matches were rotated between the three countries: India (Calcutta), Sri Lanka (Colombo) and Pakistan (Lahore), while the final was held in Dhaka, Bangladesh as a neutral venue.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] Pakistan beat Sri Lanka by an innings and 175 in the final to become the first Asian Test Champions and received US$250,000 in prize money.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] Sri Lanka, the losing finalists, were awarded US$145,000, and India, the losers of the first round, US$100,000.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] 'Man of the Series', Wasim Akram, won US$20,000, while 'Man of the Match' winners received US$5,000 in prize money.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] The matches were officiated by two independent umpires of the ICC panel.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] This was the first time that this had occurred, traditionally one ICC umpire and one home umpire stand in Test matches.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] However, one home umpire was selected as the Third Umpire in each Test match.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] The ICC Match referee for the entire Championship was Cammie Smith of the West Indies.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] A scoring system was devised by the Asian Test Championship Technical Committee consisting of Duleep Mendis (tournament director), Ashantha De Mel, Sunil Gavaskar and Majid Khan.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] It was based on the systems used in the Asian countries' domestic leagues.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] Bonus points were awarded to teams for good bowling and batting performances (*see table below*).
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] A maximum of 20 points could be gained in one match (including the 12 match winning points).
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] The bonus bowling and batting points were confined to the first 100 overs of the first innings.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] The two teams with the highest number of points qualify for the final.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] If two teams are tied on points, the team with a better run rate in the first 100 overs will go through.
[src:asian-test-championship/1998-99-asian-test-championship] If the final ends in a draw, the side with the higher bonus points will win.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Bangladesh, Pakistan and Sri Lanka competed in the second Asian Test Championship between August 2001 and March 2002.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] India pulled out of the tournament due to political tensions with Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Pakistan and Sri Lanka both played Bangladesh in the two round robin matches.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] A win was worth 16 or 12 points, a tie 8 points and no points were awarded for a draw or loss.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Additionally, bonus points were awarded to teams for bowling and batting performances.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Pakistan and Sri Lanka qualified for the final after convincingly beating Bangladesh in Multan and Colombo, respectively.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The final was held at Gaddafi Stadium in Lahore, Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Sri Lanka beat Pakistan by 8 wickets to win the second Asian Test championship.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The 2001–02 Asian Test Championship was originally planned to include all four Asian ICC full-members (Bangladesh, India, Pakistan and Sri Lanka).
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] However, before the tournament started, India's participation was put in doubt.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Initially, the BCCI requested the ACC to change the venue of the final (Dhaka) of the championship.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The BCCI requested that if Bangladesh did not reach the final, the match should not be held in Dhaka, and if India and Pakistan were to meet in the final, it should be held in India, and if an India–Sri Lanka final was to take place, it should be held in Sri Lanka.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The BCCI stated that if the venue for the final was not changed it would be difficult for India to participate in the championship.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Following this, the BCCI commented that India's participation in the championship and selection of the team would depend on permission from the Indian government.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] India's delay in confirming their participation in the championship resulted in the ACC threatening that the tournament would go ahead as scheduled without India.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] However the BCCI reacted strongly to the threat, claiming that "[a] decision will be taken shortly" and that the delay doid not "[construe] that India has pulled out of the championship".
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] A week before the championship was scheduled to begin, the BCCI announced that India would not participate in the tournament.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] This decision was reported to have been taken by Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee and other government ministers after a meeting with the BCCI.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] It was widely understood that India's withdrawal was due to political tensions between India and Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Indian sports minister Uma Bharti stated that cricketing ties between the two countries would resume after the normalization of their political ties.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Indian players' security and safety in Pakistan was also noted to be a major concern.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] As expected, the ACC reacted angrily to India's decision; it confirmed that the tournament would be rescheduled and go ahead with only three teams.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The PCB expressed regret over India's decision not to participate in the championship.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Tauqir Zia, was dismayed over the Indian government's decision to go back on their commitment, which was a guarantee that India would have no objection playing multilateral tournaments which included Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The ICC was expected to sanction or fine the BCCI for their actions.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The ACC and PCB were expected to experience a financial impact due to India's decision.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Pakistan in particular were unhappy since Pakistan's tour of India in 1999 helped raise millions of dollars in revenue for the BCCI.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] India had already cancelled a tour to Pakistan earlier in the year.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Additionally, after the first Test, the Bangladesh Cricket Board reported that they were fearing bankruptcy due to India's withdrawal from the tournament.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The director of the BCB, Ashraf-ul-Haq, commented that funds that would have been generated by the ACC from the championship would be used to invest in Bangladesh cricket as well as other minor countries, without which the BCB faced serious financial problems.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Ashraf planned on condemning the BCCI in the following ICC executive and ACC meetings.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Former Pakistan Test players, including Intikhab Alam, Haseeb Ahsan, and Wasim Akram, accused India of withdrawing due to fear of losing to Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Tournament captains, Waqar Younis (Pakistan) and Naimur Rahman (Bangladesh) expressed India's absence as a disappointment.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The Pakistan Cricket Board protested the appointment of John Reid as match referee for the 1st match of the 2001–02 Asian Test Championship.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] John Reid had been involved in controversies involving the Pakistan team; he had fined and suspended Waqar Younis and Azhar Mahmood for ball tampering and had been involved in reporting Shoaib Akhtar's suspect bowling action to the ICC.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Pakistan used the precedent that Sri Lanka had successfully removed Australian umpire Darrell Hair from their matches during the 1999 Cricket World Cup.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Hair had called Sri Lankan off-spinner Muttiah Muralitharan for throwing during a tour of Australia.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] However, ICC policies do not permit any member country to veto the appointment of independent referees or umpires.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The ICC rejected Pakistan's formal complaint, and the ICC chief executive officer Malcolm Speed assured that the PCB had confirmed that John Reid would receive the same courtesies that are extended to all ICC officials visiting Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] John Reid did not comment on the protest, but expressed disappointment and that he was still available to go to the match and do the job he had been appointed to.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Wasim Akram and Mushtaq Ahmed were left out of the initial Pakistan training squad before the tournament.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] This was done to make room for younger players, however, Akram did feature in the first Test match but failed to record a wicket.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Prior to the championship, the Pakistan Cricket Board formally announced that Richard Pybus would be the new coach of the Pakistan team for at least three series.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The scoring system used for the 2001–02 Asian Test Championship was a revised version of the first system used in the 1998–99 Asian Test Championship.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The Asian Cricket Council approved the revisions brought forward by the technical committee compromising of Sunil Gavaskar (India), Zaheer Abbas(Pakistan), Ashantha De Mel (Sri Lanka) and Gazi Ashraf (Bangladesh).
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Points for winning the match were kept at 12, however additional points were given for an innings victory.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Points for a tie were increased from 6 to 8.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] A maximum of 24 points could be gained in one match (including the 16 match winning points).
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] For the 2001–02 Championship, the bonus point system was changed, 400+ runs and 10 wickets to achieve maximum points (increased for 350+ and 9–10 from the previous championship).
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The first Test match of the Championship was between Bangladesh and Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] It was held in Multan, at the newly renovated $2.5 million Multan Cricket Stadium.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] This was the first Test match to be held in Multan since 1980–81 when the West Indies drew a match with Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Being the first match in the stadium, the nature of the pitch and ground was unknown, however a result was expected.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] This was the first Test match between the two sides.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The previous international cricket match between the two sides was at the 1999 Cricket World Cup when Bangladesh upset Pakistan to win its first One Day International against a Test team.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Bangladesh was granted Test status only 14 months prior to the championship; this was their fourth Test match, having played India once and Zimbabwe twice losing on all three occasions.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Before the match, Bangladesh captain had ruled out the possibility of a repeat upset while batsmen Al Sahariar revealed that the aim for the team was to play the full five days.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The Bangladesh team had engaged notable former cricketers Javed Miandad of Pakistan, Andy Roberts of West Indies and Trevor Chappell of Australia as coaches, to strengthen their side.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] However, monsoon weather had hampered their preparations for the tournament.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] For Pakistan, Saqlain Mushtaq was left out of the side due domestic conflicts in England.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Taufeeq Umar and Shoaib Malik were included in the initial 16-man squad; both players earned their first Test cap in this match.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Wasim Akram, initially left out of the 27-man training squad, was included in the final 16 and 11, taking Shoaib Akhtar's place, after a positive performance in a first-class match between PCB XI and Bangladesh.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Pakistan entered the match as clear favorites, despite having failed to win a Test series at home since 1997, when Wasim Akram captained the side to a 3–0 whitewash over the West Indies.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Since then, Pakistan has lost series against Zimbabwe, Sri Lanka, England and Australia.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Bangladesh won the toss and elected to bat, however they made a poor start to the match, being bowled out for 134 in 41.1 overs.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] None of the Bangladeshi batsmen scored 20 runs, while Danish Kaneria took 6 wickets.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Pakistan made a confident start to their innings, reaching 219/2 at the end of the day.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Saeed Anwar top scored on the day, making 101 from 104 deliveries.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] He reach 4000 Test runs in this innings, joining the likes of Javed Miandad, Saleem Malik, Inzamam-ul-Haq, Zaheer Abbas and Mudassar Nazar as the only Pakistanis to do so.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Pakistan ended the day with an 84 run lead with 8 wickets in hand.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Pakistan added to their overnight score on the 2nd day, amassing a total of 546/3 (declared), creating a 412 first innings lead.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Five players scored centuries: Saeed Anwar (101), Taufeeq Umar(104), Inzamam-ul-Haq (105*), Yousuf Youhana (102*) and Abdul Razzaq (110*).
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Taufeeq Umar became the 8th Pakistani batsmen to score a century on debut, while Razzaq's was the second fastest century by a Pakistani (after Majid Khan).
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Inzamam-ul-Haq retired hurt (dehydration) when the score was at 381/3.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The five centuries in one innings equaled a world record set by Australia in 1954–55 against the West Indies in Kingston, Jamaica.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Bangladesh started their innings on the 2nd day with 19 overs remaining.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] They closed at 55/3 with Habibul Bashar not out on 19.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Pakistan won the match when Bangladesh were bowled out on the 3rd day; Man of the Match, Kaneria took 6/52 for a career best match total of 12/94.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Habibul Bashar was the only batsmen to offer any resistance, scoring an unbeaten 56.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The inning and 264 runs victory was the 6th largest in Test cricket history.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] For the second time in Test history two separate century partnerships for the same wicket in the same innings were recorded.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Inzamam-ul-Haq and Yousuf Youhana added 123 (unbroken) for the fourth wicket and then Yousuf Youhana and Abdur Razzaq added 165 (unbroken) for the fourth wicket.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The latter partnership is considered "fourth" wicket because Inzamam-ul-Haq retired hurt and was not out.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The Pakistan v Bangladesh and the concurrent Sri Lanka v India (3rd Test at Colombo) Test matches provided the unique feat of centuries on test debuts on successive days in two separate Test matches.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Additionally, the Test match was the hottest ever, with temperatures in excess of 38 degrees Celsius (100 degree Fahrenheit) on each day.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Wasim Akram was criticised by the media for a poor performance in which he did not take a wicket.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] However skipper Waqar Younis backed Akram saying that he was unlucky with a couple of dropped chances.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Bangladesh coach Trevor Chappell and captain Naimur Rahman were critical of the Tigers batting performance.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Chappell also added that Kaneria did not "deserve" 12 wickets.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] After the match, it was reported that Saeed Anwar's young daughter died.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] This event led to his eventual move away from cricket.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Pakistan received the maximum 24 points for their victory; 16 for winning by an innings and 4 each for batting and bowling performances.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The second Test of the Championship was held at the Sinhalese Sports Club Ground in Colombo between Bangladesh and Sri Lanka.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] It was the first Test between the two sides and to mark the occasion, the Board of Control for Cricket in Sri Lanka (BCCSL) allowed free entry at five enclosures at the stadium.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The BCCSL also established prize money for the match, with the winning team earning SLR 70,000, the losing team SLR 40,000 and the Man of the Match earning SLR 25,000.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] This Test was the second meeting of the two sides in international cricket; Sri Lanka beat Bangladesh in an ODI during the 1997 Asia Cup.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Prior to this match, Bangladesh had lost four Test matches in a row, and their coach Trevor Chappell was expecting this Test to be a learning experience for the side rather than an opportunity to win their first match.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Following Bangladesh's batting collapse in the first match of the championship against Pakistan at the hands of leg spinner Danish Kaneria, Bangladesh was expected to perform better with the bat, especially against the in-form Muralitharan who took 23 wickets in 3 Tests against India.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Sri Lanka entered the match after a 2–1 series win over India.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Sanath Jayasuriya, the Sri Lanka captain warned ahead of the game that his team can not afford to relax and was expecting good performance against the newest Test nation.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Historically, Sri Lanka have had a winning record at the Sinhalese Sports Club Ground, with Chaminda Vaas and Muralitharan taking career bests at this venue.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The pitch was not expected to deteriorate in the first three days and was assumed to support fast bowlers.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Sri Lanka pacer Dilhara Fernando was ruled out due a groin strain and was replaced by Ravindra Pushpakumara.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] Additionally, under-performing batsman Russel Arnold and fast bowler Dulip Liyanage were replaced by Michael Vandort and Ruchira Perera respectively.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] For Bangladesh, Akram Khan and Enamul Haque were replaced by Mohammad Ashraful and Al Sahariar.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] This was the first Test match for Vandort and Ashraful.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] After both Pakistan and Sri Lanka defeated Bangladesh in their respective round-robin matches, the two teams agreed to play a straight final instead of their meaningless round-robin match.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] The PCB and Board of Control for Cricket in Sri Lanka agreed to play the final match at Gaddafi Stadium in Lahore, Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-02-asian-test-championship] It marked the return of international cricket to Pakistan after the 2001 US invasion of Afghanistan prompted the cancellation of tours by New Zealand and Sri Lanka, and the rescheduling of the West Indies series to Sharjah.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The **2001–2002 India–Pakistan standoff** was a military standoff between India and Pakistan that resulted in the massing of troops on both sides of the border and along the Line of Control (LoC) in the region of Kashmir.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] This was the second major military standoff between India and Pakistan following the successful detonation of nuclear devices by both countries in 1998, after the Kargil War of 1999.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] India claimed that the attacks were carried out by two Pakistan-based terror groups fighting in Indian-administered Kashmir—Lashkar-e-Taiba and Jaish-e-Mohammed, both of whom India has said are backed by Pakistan's ISI–a charge that Pakistan has denied.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Farooq Abdullah the then chief minister of Jammu and Kashmir state urged India to launch a war against militant training camps across the border in Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] In Western media, coverage of the standoff focused on the possibility of a nuclear war between the two countries and the implications of the potential conflict on the American-led "Global War on Terrorism" in nearby Afghanistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Tensions de-escalated following international diplomatic mediation which resulted in the October 2002 withdrawal of Indian and Pakistani troops from the international border.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Towards the end of the protracted military standoff, in a surreptitious operation, India's Jat Regiment occupied a strategically important mountain peak on the Pakistani side of the LoC near Dras, Point 5070, and subsequently rechristened it *Balwan*.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] This had implications for the Pakistani army, which was accustomed to occupying the peak during summer, as the peak gave India a vantage view of Gultari valley which sustained Pakistani posts in Dras.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] In consequence, the Pakistani army dispensed its entire chain of command, including the Pakistani Brigade Commander and GOC of the Northern Areas over the loss of this peak, while their Indian counterpart Lt.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Deepak Summanwar was felicitated with an Uttam Yudh Seva Medal as a recognition of India's complete domination of the boundary area near Dras.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On the morning of 13 December 2001, a cell of five armed men attacked the Parliament of India by breaching the security cordon at Gate 12.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The five men killed seven people before being shot dead by the Indian Security Forces.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] World leaders and leaders in nearby countries strongly condemned the attack on the parliament, including Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 14 December, the ruling Indian National Democratic Alliance blamed Pakistan-based Lashkar-e-Taiba (LeT) and Jaish-e-Mohammed (JeM) for the attack.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Advani claimed, "*we have received some clues about yesterday's incident, which shows that a neighboring country, and some terrorist organizations active there are behind it*", in an indirect reference to Pakistan and Pakistan-based militant groups.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The same day, in a démarche to Pakistan's High Commissioner to India, Ashraf Jehangir Qazi, India demanded that Pakistan stop the activities of LeT and JeM, apprehend the organisation's leaders and their access to all financial assets.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Following the Indian Government's statements, Pakistan put its military into full combat readiness the same day.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 20 December, amid calls from the United States, Russia, and United Nations to exercise restraint, India mobilised and deployed its troops to Kashmir and Indian Punjab in what was India's largest military mobilisation since the 1971 conflict.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The Indian codename for the mobilisation was Operation *Parakram*.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] It would start with an airstrike by the Indian Air Force's Tiger Squadron to attack zones with a large concentration of camps.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Special forces of the Indian Army would then launch a limited ground offensive to further neutralize the terrorist camps and help to occupy the dominant positions on the LoC.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] 14 January 2002, was decided as the tentative D-day.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] According to the Indian strategy, a limited strike in the Pakistan administered Kashmir was preferred as it would convey the Indian resolve to Pakistan and yet keep the international retribution levels that are manageable.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Indian actions would then be comparable to the ongoing US offensive in Afghanistan against Osama bin Laden's Al-Qaeda terrorists.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The CCS had weighed in the possibility of Pakistan launching an all-out offensive as a response to the Indian strikes.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The intelligence assessment suggested that the Pakistani Army was not well prepared.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] This further minimized the chances of Pakistan launching a full-scale war.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The Indian plans were strengthened by a strong economy with low inflation, high petroleum, and forex reserves.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Finance minister Yashwant Sinha announced that the Indian economy was prepared for war, in spite of being the final option.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The limited strike served as a tactical option.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The troop build-up signaled "India's seriousness" to the international community.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] If Pakistan's strategy did not change then India would have no other option.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] In late December, both countries moved ballistic missiles closer to each other's border, and mortar and artillery fire was reported in Kashmir.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] By January 2002, India had mobilized around 500,000 troops and three armored divisions on Pakistan's border, concentrated along the Line of Control in Kashmir.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Pakistan responded similarly, deploying around 300,000 troops to that region.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The tensions were partially defused after Musharraf's speech on 12 January promising action on terror emanating from Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Artillery duels were commonplace during the protracted military confrontations.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] In one such instance, well over 40 Pakistani soldiers perished on Point 5353 near Dras when Indian troops from nearby Point 5165, Point 5240 and Point 5100 commenced artillery fire on the Pakistani post, rendering the Pakistanis unable to reinforce their troops.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] India initiated its diplomatic offensive by recalling Indian high commissioner and the civilian flights from Pakistan were banned.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Pakistan picked up the war signals and began mobilization of its military and initiated diplomatic talks with US president George W.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] American Secretary of State Colin Powell engaged with India and Pakistan to reduce tensions.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] In the first week of January, British prime minister Tony Blair visited India with a message that he was pressurizing Pakistani president Musharraf.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The US declared LeT and JeM as foreign terrorist groups.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 8 January 2002, Indian Home Minister L.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Advani visited the US, where he was informed about the contents of the upcoming landmark speech by Musharraf.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 12 January 2002, President Pervez Musharraf gave a speech intended to reduce tensions with India.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] He for the first time condemned the attack on Parliament as a terrorist attack and compared it with the 11 September attacks.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] He declared in his speech that terrorism was unjustified in the name of Kashmir and Pakistan would combat extremism on its own soil.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Pakistan would resolve Kashmir with dialogue and no organization will be allowed to carry out terrorism *under the pretext of Kashmir*.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] As demanded by India, he also announced plans for the regulation of madrasas and banning the known terrorist groups that were operating out of Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] He announced a formal ban on five jihadi organizations, that included Jaish-e-Mohammed and Lashkar-e-Taiba engaged in militancy in Kashmir.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Vajpayee though skeptic of the seriousness of Musharraf's pledges, decided not to carry out the military attack planned for 14 January.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Tensions escalated significantly in May 2002.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 14 May, three suicidal terrorists attacked an army camp at Kaluchak near Jammu and killed 34 people and injured fifty more before getting killed, most of the victims were the wives and children of Indian soldiers serving in Kashmir.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The terrorist incident again revived the chance of a full-blown war.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 15 May, PM Vajpayee was quoted in the Indian Parliament saying "*Hamein pratikar karna hoga (We will have to counter it).*" American Deputy Secretary of State, Richard Armitage, quoted the incident as a trigger for further deterioration of the situation.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The Indian Cabinet had little belief that diplomatic pressure could stop Pakistan's support for the militants in Kashmir.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] India accused Pakistan that it was failing to keep its promise on ending the cross-border terrorism.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Musharraf's follow-up to his speech on 12 January was observed by India as weak and disingenuous.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Pakistan did not extradite the terrorist leaders demanded by India, and Lashkar was allowed to continue its operations in Pakistan as a charity with a new name.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] During the spring, jihadi militants started crossing the Line of Control again.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 18 May, Vajpayee reviewed the preparedness with the defence minister Fernandes, director-general military operations and military intelligence chief.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The CCS met and favored taking military action against terrorists in Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] A limited military action similar to the one planned in January was not considered viable as Pakistan had strengthened its forces on the LoC.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Any action limited to Pakistan administered Kashmir would only have limited military gains.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Indian military favored an offensive along the Indo-Pak border that will stretch the Pakistani troops and provide India access to Pakistan administered Kashmir.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The Indian armed forces accordingly prepared the plan to target the war-waging capabilities of Pakistan and destroy the terrorist camps.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The battle canvas planned for June was larger than the one planned in January.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The Indian Air Force along with the 1 Strike Corps of India would initiate an attack in Shakargarh bulge to engage Pakistan's Army Reserve North (ARN) that was spread from Muzaffarabad to Lahore.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] This would engage Pakistan's key strike corp while Indian strike formations from Eastern Command would carry out the offensive at the Line of Control and capture the strategic positions used by the terrorists for infiltrations.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The period considered was between 23 May and 10 June.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] During the end of May 2002, the Indian and Pakistani armed forces continued to be fully mobilized.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The tenor of statements published in the Indian press and intelligence information collected, pointed to an imminent invasion by India.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] An SOS sent to Israel by the Indian Defence Ministry for defense supplies during the month of June confirmed the intelligence.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 18 May, India expelled the Pakistani High Commissioner.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] That same day, thousands of villagers had to flee Pakistani artillery fire in Jammu.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 21 May, clashes killed six Pakistani soldiers and 1 Indian soldier, as well as civilians from both sides.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 22 May, Indian Prime Minister Vajpayee announced to his troops to prepare for a "decisive battle".
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Between 25 and 28 May, Pakistan conducted 3 missile tests.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] India reviewed its nuclear capability to strike back.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 7 June the Indian Air Force lost an unmanned aerial vehicle near Lahore, which Pakistan claimed to have shot down.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] As both India and Pakistan are armed with nuclear weapons, the possibility a conventional war could escalate into a nuclear one was raised several times during the standoff.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Various statements on this subject were made by Indian and Pakistani officials during the conflict, mainly concerning a no first use policy.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Indian External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh said on 5 June that India would not use nuclear weapons first, while Musharraf said on 5 June he would not renounce Pakistan's right to use nuclear weapons first.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] There was also concern that a 6 June 2002 asteroid explosion over Earth, known as the Eastern Mediterranean Event, could have caused a nuclear conflict had it exploded over India or Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Vajpayee contacted the leaders of the global community including Bush, Blair, Russian president Vladimir Putin and French president Jacques Chirac and informed them Musharraf could not deliver on his 12 January speech and the patience of the country was running out.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] In the diplomacy that followed, Bush, Putin, Blair and Japanese prime minister Junichiro Koizumi requested Vajpayee to avoid taking the extreme step.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The global community informed India that it would negotiate with Musharraf to clarify his position on stopping the cross-border infiltration.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Attempts to defuse the situation continued.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The Russian president Vladimir Putin tried to mediate a solution, but in vain.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Restraint was urged by the global community as there were fears that Pakistan would proceed to use its nuclear weapons in the face to counter its conventional asymmetry as compared to the Indian armed forces.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] In April, in an interview to German magazine Der Spiegel Musharraf had already hinted that he was willing to use nukes against India.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Pakistan's nuclear threats led to US Secretary of State Powell contacting Musharraf at five occasions in the last week of May and reading the riot act.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 5 June 2002, American Deputy Secretary of State Richard Armitage visited Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] He asked Musharraf if he would "permanently" end cross-border infiltration and help to dismantle the infrastructure used for terrorism.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 6 June 2002, Musharraf 's commitment was conveyed to Powell, and to India after his arrival.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 10 June 2002, Powell announced Musharraf's promise to the global community, after which India called off its strike plans.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] A full-frontal invasion would have translated into war.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Political logic implied it was better to give another chance to Musharraf.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The military build-up on the border by India in January and June had forced both the international community and Pakistan into action.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 29 July 2002 for the first time after the end of the Kargil war, India used air power to attack positions held by the Pakistani forces at Loonda Post on the Indian side of the Line of Control in the Machil sector.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Eight IAF Mirage 2000 H aircraft dropped precision-guided bombs weighing 1,000-pounds to destroy four bunkers that were occupied by Pakistan.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The forward trenches prepared by Indian troops in earlier years were also occupied by the Pakistani forces and 155-millimetre Bofors howitzers were used to hit them.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] According to Indian military intelligence officials, at least 28 Pakistani soldiers were killed in the fighting.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The air assault was conducted in daylight and to demonstrate India's willingness to escalate the conflict in response to provocations.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] This had implications for the Pakistani army, which was accustomed to occupying the peak during summer, as the peak gave India a vantage view of the Gultari valley, which sustained Pakistani posts in Dras.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] In consequence, the Pakistani army dispensed its entire chain of command, including the Pakistani Brigade Commander and GOC of the Northern Areas, over the loss of this peak, while their Indian counterpart Lt.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Deepak Summanwar was felicitated with an Uttam Yudh Seva Medal as a recognition of India's domination of the boundary area near Dras.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Pakistani army troops stationed near the post in the Kupwara sector's Kel area of the LoC had been shelling the Indian positions across the LoC.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] India suspected a troop build-up situation near the border post that was similar to Kargil.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Indian army planned retaliation by sending troops to attack the Pakistani posts.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The initial ground attack to retake the post failed, with the Indian army suffering 11 casualties.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Later on, after deliberations with the then Army Chief, General Sundararajan Padmanabhan, the plan was modified and instead of only a ground assault, the decision was made to first attack Pakistani positions using the IAF jets followed by a ground assault by the Indian Special Forces.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] At 1:30 pm on 2 August, IAF's LGB capable Mirage 2000 H fighter aircraft loaded with laser-guided weapons bombed the Pakistani bunkers located in the Kel.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The attack destroyed the bunkers with an unknown number of casualties.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] While tensions remained high throughout the next few months, both governments began easing the situation in Kashmir.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] By October 2002, India had begun to demobilise their troops along her border and later Pakistan did the same, and in November 2003 a cease-fire between the two nations was signed.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The Indian casualties were up to 1,874, including 798 fatal.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The Indian cost for the buildup was $3 billion to $4 billion while Pakistan's was $1.4 billion.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The standoff led to a total of 155,000 Indians and 45,000 Pakistanis displaced, per Pakistani media estimates.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] One of the reasons for the failure of Operation Parakram is described to be the slow mobilisation of 500,000 troops.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] It took nearly three weeks for India to completely move 500,000 troops, 3 armoured divisions, and other supporting units to the border.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] The delay allowed Pakistan to move its own 300,000 troops along with the supporting units to the border.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Lacking strategic surprise, Indian military decided to withdraw its troops.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] On 5 November 2011, former Indian naval chief, Admiral Sushil Kumar, claimed that operation Parakram lacked clear objectives.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] He described the operation as a "punishing mistake" for India.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Moreover, he said that Operation Parakram, may in fact have encouraged both Pakistan and China to increase cross-border violations.
[src:asian-test-championship/2001-2002-india-pakistan-standoff] Had India tried a similar operation against China, it would have been a fatal blunder for India.
[src:asian-test-championship/2014-acc-elite-league] The first tournament of second division of ACC Premier League was held in Singapore between 7–13 June 2014.
[src:asian-test-championship/2014-acc-elite-league] Singapore won the tournament and qualified for 2016 ACC Premier League.
[src:asian-test-championship/2014-acc-elite-league] Saudi Arabia finishing second qualified for 2015 ICC World Cricket League Division Six.
[src:asian-test-championship/acc-championship] The **ACC Championship** was a cancelled two-day cricket tournament run by the Asian Cricket Council that is contested between its members nations.
[src:asian-test-championship/acc-championship] The first tournament was scheduled to be held in December 2014.
[src:asian-test-championship/acc-championship] It was canceled due to the busy preparation schedules of Afghanistan and UAE for the 2015 ICC Cricket World Cup.
[src:asian-test-championship/acc-championship] The 2014 ACC Championship was scheduled to be the first tournament of the ACC Championship, to be held in the United Arab Emirates on 7–14 December 2014.
[src:asian-test-championship/acc-championship] The top four teams from the 2014 ACC Premier League, Afghanistan, UAE, Nepal and Oman had qualified for the championship.
[src:asian-test-championship/acc-championship] Due to the busy preparation schedules of Afghanistan and UAE for 2015 ICC Cricket World Cup, the tournament was cancelled.
[src:asian-test-championship/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] The **ACC Fast Track Countries Tournament** was a three-day cricket tournament run by the Asian Cricket Council (ACC), contested between its top-ranking ICC associate members.
[src:asian-test-championship/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] It was played three times between 2004 and 2006, and then replaced by the ACC Twenty20 Cup.
[src:asian-test-championship/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] Some matches in the second edition of the tournament held first-class status, as they were simultaneously ICC Intercontinental Cup matches.
[src:asian-test-championship/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] Hong Kong, the UAE and Nepal all qualified for the 2005 ICC Intercontinental Cup as a result of their top three finish in the tournament.
[src:asian-test-championship/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] A separate final was originally set to be held, but as Hong Kong and the UAE topped the group with only their group match to take place, it was decided to make the final group match the overall tournament final.
[src:asian-test-championship/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] The UAE beat Hong Kong by five wickets in that final.
[src:asian-test-championship/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] Matches in this tournament between Hong Kong, Nepal and the UAE also counted towards the 2005 ICC Intercontinental Cup.
[src:asian-test-championship/asian-test-championship] The **Asian Test Championship** was a Test cricket tournament contested by the Test-playing nations of Asia: India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka and Bangladesh.
[src:asian-test-championship/asian-test-championship] It was originally planned to be held every two years, alternately with the Asia Cup.
[src:asian-test-championship/asian-test-championship] The third Championship was delayed for four years due to conflicting tours of the participating members.
[src:asian-test-championship/asian-test-championship] In 2006, the Asian Cricket Council cancelled the Asian Test Championship, as well as the Asian and African Cup, due to the tightly packed International cricket tour schedule.
[src:asian-test-championship/asian-test-championship] The tournament winners were Pakistan in 1998–99 and Sri Lanka in 2001–02.
[src:asian-test-championship/asian-test-championship] The Asian Test Championship is only the second example of a Test cricket tournament involving more than two teams, the first being the 1912 Triangular Tournament, which was held between Australia, England and South Africa.
[src:asian-test-championship/asian-test-championship] This tournament was considered to be the predecessor to the ICC World Test Championship that the International Cricket Council (ICC) was planning for the 9 member nations.
[src:asian-test-championship/asian-test-championship] Bangladesh, Pakistan, Sri Lanka competed in the second Asian Test Championship between August 2001 and March 2002.
[src:asian-test-championship/asian-test-championship] A win was worth 16 points, a tie 8 points and no points were awarded for a draw or loss.
[src:asian-test-championship/asian-test-championship] In addition to this, bonus points were awarded to teams for bowling and batting performances.
[src:asian-test-championship/asian-test-championship] Pakistan and Sri Lanka qualified for the final after convincingly beating Bangladesh in Multan Cricket Stadium in Pakistan and Colombo in Sri Lanka.
[src:asian-test-championship/asian-test-championship] Sri Lanka defeated Pakistan by 8 wickets to win the second Asian Test championship.
